org.biopax.paxtools.controller
Class PropertyReasoner

java.lang.Object
  org.biopax.paxtools.controller.Traverser
      org.biopax.paxtools.controller.AbstractTraverser
          org.biopax.paxtools.controller.PropertyReasoner
All Implemented Interfaces:
Visitor
public class PropertyReasoner
extends AbstractTraverser

A tool to set or infer a particular BioPAX property for an object and all its children. For best (consistent) results, it's recommended to generally start from a "root" element, or at least form the parent-most one, that have given property. However, for some (if not most of) BioPAX properties, except for, e.g., 'dataSource', 'xref', 'organism', 'cellularLocation', - using of this tool does NOT make sense; i.e., one should not normally "infer" (apply to children elements) such properties as 'displayName', 'ph', 'nextStep' (for sure!), etc.. Tip: use with care; write tests for your case!

setOverride

protected void setOverride(boolean override)
Sets the override mode. Following the A,B,C example in the run(BioPAXElement, Object) method: - when override is true, and property is a functional BioPAX property: A, B and C all get the X value (unless valueStack was not null, and they are to get the default values). - when override is false, and property is a functional BioPAX property: A, B - stay unmodified, C acquires Y values (B's). - when override is false, and property is a multiple cardinality property: - B and C will have both X and Y values.

Parameters:
override - the override mode to set (see the above explanation)
See Also:
run(BioPAXElement, Object)

run

protected void run(BioPAXElement element,
                   java.lang.Object defaultValue)
Basic, universal method (used by others in this class) - updates the property values of a BioPAX element and its children. The root element (first parameter) does not necessarily have the property though. For example, if X is the property value(s) of A, Y - value of B, and C has no value (unknown); A has a child B, which in turn has child C (not necessarily direct child); A, B, C are instances of one of classes listed in domains (if any). Then the following results are expected (note: even if, e.g., B would not pass the domains filter, the results for A and C will be the same): - X will be considered a replacement/addition to Y for B, and both X and Y values - for C. The result also depends on override, the default valueStack and the property's cardinality. The default value (a Set of values, object or primitive) is to be applied when both current and parent's property values are yet unknown. However, if override is true, the default values, if given, will unconditionally replace all existing ones. Warning: when the defaultValue is null or empty set, and override==true, this will clear the property values of all corresponding elements.

Parameters:
element -
defaultValue - a default values or set of values
See Also:
setDomains(Class...), setOverride(boolean)
